            "comments": [
                {
                    "file": "meta-yadro/recipes-yadro/cli/obmc-yadro-hostpwrctl_git.bb",
                    "line": 13,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Ed Tanous",
                        "email": "ed@tanous.net",
                        "username": "edtanous"
                    },
                    "message": "Please don't add recipes that point to company-specific forks of openbmc.  It essentially bypasses our code review process and prevents us from reusing code on other systems.  If this power control is so different from the existing solutions that it really needs a new repository, and can't just be a configure option on an existing one, then start a discussion and request a new repository, but I suspect that this behavior could easily live in one of the applications we already have."
                },
                {
                    "file": "meta-yadro/recipes-yadro/cli/obmc-yadro-hostpwrctl_git.bb",
                    "line": 13,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrei Kartashev",
                        "email": "a.kartashev@yadro.com",
                        "username": "alatarum"
                    },
                    "message": "What existing one do you propose to use? This it CLI util which send some DBUS requests and control answers/state after timeout to provide user information about if the operation was success.\n\nThe policy (https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/meta-layer-guidelines.md) asks us to use only \"well maintained open source projects\", but this is our vendor-owned repo, it is OpenSource and it is well-maintained  enough for our purposes.\nIt is not worth to move all the vendor-repos to obmc github unless any other community members want to use them all. That is how it was e.g. with phosphor-hostlogger: we first develop it in our github, but then someone said they want to use it also and we move it to openbmc."
                }
            ],
